  "prompt": "How has legislation evolved to combat money laundering?",
  "response": "Legislation combating money laundering has evolved significantly over time:\n\n1. Early Stages\n- Bank Secrecy Act (1970) in the United States\n- Initial focus on reporting large cash transactions\n- Limited international cooperation\n\n2. International Developments\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) established in 1989\n- Developed global standards for anti-money laundering (AML) practices\n- Created comprehensive recommendations for national regulations\n\n3. Key Legislative Milestones\n- USA PATRIOT Act (2001)\n- Enhanced reporting requirements\n- Increased financial institution accountability\n- Strengthened cross-border transaction monitoring\n\n4. Technological Adaptations\n- Regulations addressing digital currencies\n- Enhanced electronic transaction tracking\n- Requirements for cryptocurrency exchanges\n\n5. Recent Trends\n- Stricter Know Your Customer (KYC) protocols\n- Advanced customer due diligence\n- Increased penalties for non-compliance\n- Greater emphasis on beneficial ownership transparency\n\n6. Global Regulatory Convergence\n- More harmonized international standards\n- Improved information sharing between jurisdictions\n- Coordinated enforcement mechanisms\n\nLegislation continues evolving to address emerging financial technologies and sophisticated laundering techniques.",
